1. The split heuristic (sharpest drop in rolling average sentence length) places the
   split at sentence 845, but the output shows the Gerty half has 13,257 tokens vs.
   Bloom's 3,731 -- a roughly 78/22 split. This is far from the expected 40-60% range
   noted in the rubric. The heuristic may be triggering on a local dip rather than the
   true Gerty-to-Bloom transition. Consider using a known textual marker (e.g., searching
   for "Mr Bloom" appearing after a long Gerty stretch, or the line beginning "Tight
   boots? No. She's lame!" which is a well-known transition point) rather than relying
   purely on sentence-length statistics.

2. Semicolon rate is 0.0000 for all four texts. This is likely because the source text
   files do not contain semicolons (Joyce's punctuation in Ulysses is unconventional),
   or the encoding uses a different character. The metric is wasted; consider replacing
   it with question mark frequency or ellipsis frequency, both of which would be more
   informative for distinguishing Gerty's exclamatory style from Bloom's interrogative
   one.

3. Em-dash rate is 0.0000 for Bloom's Nausicaa half but 0.07 for Calypso and
   Lestrygonians. This could be a genuine stylistic difference in the source text or a
   Unicode issue (en-dash vs. em-dash vs. double-hyphen). Worth verifying that the dash
   character used in the source files is consistent.

4. Yule's K is listed in the exercise prompt as part of the vocabulary richness metrics
   but is not computed in the script. The stylometric_profile() function computes TTR and
   hapax ratio but omits Yule's K entirely.

5. The exercise asks for visualization ("Visualize the two profiles side by side"), and
   matplotlib is imported and configured with the Agg backend, but no plots are actually
   generated or saved. The visualization component is missing.

6. The cliche ratio (1.46x) falls slightly below the rubric's expected threshold of
   >1.5x. This may be because the reference corpus (first 5 Gutenberg texts) is not
   well-matched to the sentimental/romance register of Gerty's prose. Using a reference
   corpus of Victorian sentimental fiction would likely produce a higher ratio.

7. The Burrows' Delta implementation computes z-scores using the corpus mean and standard
   deviation, then measures delta for each corpus text against the test text. This is
   correct per the standard formulation, but the corpus used for computing the mean/std
   includes the Bloom-Nausicaa half, which means the test text's own "other half" is
   part of the normalization basis. This is a minor methodological concern but worth
   noting.

8. The exercise mentions comparing Gerty to "actual Victorian sentimental fiction" as an
   optional reference corpus for Burrows' Delta. This is not attempted. Adding even one
   or two Gutenberg sentimental texts (e.g., Maria Cummins' "The Lamplighter", which
   Joyce explicitly references) would strengthen the analysis.
